  <!-- ===== PEER-REVIEWED ===== -->
  <section class="section" id="peer" aria-labelledby="peer-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Peer-reviewed academic · 9 sources</span>
      <h2 id="peer-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Peer-reviewed</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        The empirical and theoretical core. Where this project's claims about
        digital twins as personalization technology, customer experience tools,
        and underwriting instruments come from.
      </p>

      <ul class="cite-list" style="margin-top: 32px;">

        <li data-n="01">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Bäumer et al. — Mirroring Privacy Risks with Digital Twins</h4>
          <p><em>SN Computer Science, 5,</em> Article 1109 (2024). Demonstrates how disparate open-data fragments combine into a complete personal profile via a digital twin, and proposes a pseudonymization-and-synthetic-data framework.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>privacy</code> · <code>ethics</code> · <code>consent</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s42979-024-03413-z" target="_blank" rel="noopener">link.springer.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="02">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--orange">UNF library</span>
          <h4>Hornik &amp; Rachamim — AI-enabled Consumer Digital Twins</h4>
          <p><em>Management Review Quarterly,</em> advance online publication (2025). Conceptual platform for AI-built consumer digital twins using the <code>MODA</code> framework. Defines the consumer twin as a "synthetic agent" replicating cognition, preferences, and decision-making.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>customer-engagement</code> · <code>personalization</code> · <code>AI</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11301-025-00527-3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">link.springer.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="03">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--orange">UNF library</span>
          <h4>McColl-Kennedy et al. — Digital Twins: A Game Changer in CX</h4>
          <p><em>Journal of Service Management,</em> advance online publication (2025). Introduces digital twins to CX literature with a conceptual framework and roadmap; demonstrates applicability in B2B shipping, retail food, and healthcare.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>customer-experience</code> · <code>service-management</code> · <code>personalization</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.emerald.com/insight/content/doi/10.1108/JOSM-01-2025-0036" target="_blank" rel="noopener">emerald.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="04">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Mitu &amp; Zglavoci — Finance 4.0: Digital Twin Technology</h4>
          <p><em>The Young Economists Journal, 42,</em> 23–32 (2024). Bibliometric analysis of 8,942 Web of Science articles on digital twins. Cites Altair: 50% of BFSI use DT for behavioral modeling.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>finance</code> · <code>adoption</code> · <code>bibliometric</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://ideas.repec.org/a/lum/rev1rl/v21y2024i42p23-32.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ideas.repec.org ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="05">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Oehlschläger et al. — How Digital Twins Impact Responsiveness</h4>
          <p><em>Schmalenbach Journal of Business Research, 76</em>(5) (2024). Applies Information Processing Theory to show how digital twins help organizations respond faster to customer demand fluctuations through real-time virtual–physical linkage.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>business-value</code> · <code>responsiveness</code> · <code>sales</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s41471-024-00202-5" target="_blank" rel="noopener">link.springer.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="06">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--orange">UNF library</span>
          <h4>Quach et al. — Digital Twins: Enhancing Personalized Experience Through Phygital Journey</h4>
          <p><em>Australasian Marketing Journal, 34</em>(1) (2026). Uses 27,148 Foursquare users and 2M+ check-ins across four cities to build digital twins via social network graphs. The most direct empirical source on personalization through DTs.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>personalization</code> · <code>phygital</code> · <code>marketing-journey</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/14413582251358859" target="_blank" rel="noopener">journals.sagepub.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="07">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Rehman — Digital Twins: A New Era in P&amp;C Insurance Underwriting</h4>
          <p><em>International Journal of Science and Research, 13</em>(6), 1072–1077 (2024). The single peer-reviewed paper directly on DT in insurance. Real-time monitoring of physical assets via continuously-updated virtual replicas.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>insurance</code> · <code>underwriting</code> · <strong>core source</strong></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.ijsr.net/archive/v13i6/SR24615114425.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ijsr.net (PDF) ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="08">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Soler-Dorda et al. — Privacy and Security Challenges of the Digital Twin: A Systematic Review</h4>
          <p><em>Journal of Universal Computer Science, 30</em>(12), 1782–1806 (2024). Systematic review of 47 publications. Six categories of risk: data privacy, security, governance, infrastructure/standards, ethics, legal/social.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>privacy</code> · <code>security</code> · <code>risk-taxonomy</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.jucs.org/jucs_30_12/privacy_and_security_challenges" target="_blank" rel="noopener">jucs.org ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="09">
          <span class="tag">peer-reviewed</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>Tao et al. — Digital Twin: A Review of the Evolution from Concept to Technology</h4>
          <p><em>Applied Sciences, 14</em>(13), 5454 (2024). Comprehensive review of DT evolution from NASA's 2010 concept to current cross-industry technology. The reference for project introduction and background.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>technology-overview</code> · <code>history</code> · <code>cross-industry</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.mdpi.com/2076-3417/14/13/5454" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mdpi.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== INDUSTRY REPORTS ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" id="industry" aria-labelledby="industry-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Industry reports · 5 sources</span>
      <h2 id="industry-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Industry research</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Quantitative adoption and market data. Where the
        survey-vs-industry-data comparison in the dashboard comes from.
      </p>

      <ul class="cite-list" style="margin-top: 32px;">

        <li data-n="10">
          <span class="tag">industry report</span>
          <span class="badge badge--blue">registration</span>
          <h4>Altair — 2023 Global Digital Twin Survey: BFSI</h4>
          <p>Altair Engineering (2023). Survey of 2,000+ specialists. 71% of BFSI already use DTs; 97% rate them critical; 64% are "highly knowledgeable"; 50% use DTs for behavioral modelling. The source that specifically pushed this project to drop the "low awareness" framing.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>adoption</code> · <code>BFSI</code> · <code>behavioral-modeling</code> · <strong>core source</strong></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://altair.com/resource/2023-digital-twin-survey-report" target="_blank" rel="noopener">altair.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="11">
          <span class="tag">industry report</span>
          <span class="badge badge--blue">registration</span>
          <h4>Capgemini &amp; Qorus — World P&amp;C Insurance Report 2023</h4>
          <p>Capgemini Research Institute (2023). The shift from insuring assets to insuring mobility. 42% of customers want a single multi-modal mobility policy; 63% of insurers worry about technology adequacy; only 21% have advanced partnership capabilities.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>market-context</code> · <code>personalization</code> · <code>P&amp;C</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.capgemini.com/insights/research-library/world-property-casualty-insurance-report" target="_blank" rel="noopener">capgemini.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="12">
          <span class="tag">industry report</span>
          <span class="badge badge--blue">registration</span>
          <h4>KPMG — Advancing AI Across Insurance</h4>
          <p>KPMG International (2024). Forecasts a $79B AI-in-insurance market by 2033. Identifies the gap between investment and adoption; interviews with Generali, PassportCard, Prudential, Zurich. Anchors the broader AI context for DTs.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>AI</code> · <code>insurance-transformation</code> · <code>adoption-gap</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://kpmg.com/xx/en/our-insights/ai-and-technology/advancing-ai-across-insurance.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">kpmg.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="13">
          <span class="tag">industry report</span>
          <span class="badge badge--orange">paywalled</span>
          <h4>Market Research Future — Digital Twin Financial Services &amp; Insurance Market 2024–2032</h4>
          <p>Market Research Future (2024). Market sizing: <code>USD 3.45B (2023)</code> → <code>USD 10.5B (2032)</code>. Used quantitatively in the introduction and background of the project. Summary free, full report paid.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>market-sizing</code> · <code>forecast</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.marketresearchfuture.com/reports/digital-twin-financial-services-market" target="_blank" rel="noopener">marketresearchfuture.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="14">
          <span class="tag">industry report</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>U.S. GAO — Science &amp; Tech Spotlight: Digital Twins</h4>
          <p>U.S. Government Accountability Office, GAO-23-106453 (2023). Government technology overview written for non-specialists. Plain-language explanation of what DTs are, how they work, where they're used, what risks they introduce. Authoritative non-vendor source.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>technology-overview</code> · <code>risk</code> · <code>plain-language</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-23-106453" target="_blank" rel="noopener">gao.gov ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== REGULATORY ===== -->
  <section class="section" id="regulatory" aria-labelledby="regulatory-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Regulatory · 2 sources</span>
      <h2 id="regulatory-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Regulators on consent and privacy</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        The legal-and-policy frame. Specifically what regulators in the EU and
        Canada are saying about consent in data-rich personalization regimes.
      </p>

      <ul class="cite-list" style="margin-top: 32px;">

        <li data-n="15">
          <span class="tag">regulatory</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>EDPB — Opinion 08/2024 on "Consent or Pay" Models</h4>
          <p>European Data Protection Board (2024). "Consent or pay" models on large platforms do not satisfy GDPR. Consent must be free, informed, specific. Binary "agree or pay" is not free consent. Direct read-across to DT-driven personalization.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>GDPR</code> · <code>consent</code> · <code>privacy</code> · <code>ethics</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.edpb.europa.eu/our-work-tools/our-documents/opinion-board-art-64/opinion-082024-valid-consent-context-consent-or_en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">edpb.europa.eu ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="16">
          <span class="tag">regulatory</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>OPC Canada — 2022–23 Departmental Results Report</h4>
          <p>Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada (2023). Three pillars: privacy as fundamental right, privacy as innovation enabler, privacy as trust accelerator. Notes AI-company investigations and Bill C-27 work.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>PIPEDA</code> · <code>Canada</code> · <code>Bill-C-27</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.priv.gc.ca/en/about-the-opc/opc-operational-reports/dpr/dpr-2022-2023/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">priv.gc.ca ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== PROFESSIONAL ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" id="professional" aria-labelledby="professional-h">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Professional publications · 5 sources</span>
      <h2 id="professional-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Practitioner perspective</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Industry voices — insurer-published, consultant-published, and
        trade-press. Used for grounding in present-day practice and for
        triangulating the academic findings against vendor and operator
        perspectives.
      </p>

      <ul class="cite-list" style="margin-top: 32px;">

        <li data-n="17">
          <span class="tag">professional</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>MAPFRE — The Use of Digital Twins in Insurance</h4>
          <p>MAPFRE (2024). Practitioner-facing overview from a major international insurer. Covers DT use in auto (telematics + behavior-based personalization), health, and property insurance. Concrete examples from inside the industry.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>insurer-practice</code> · <code>auto</code> · <code>personalization</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.mapfre.com/en/insights/innovation/digital-twins-insurance/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mapfre.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="18">
          <span class="tag">professional</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>McKinsey — Digital Twins: What Could They Do for Your Business?</h4>
          <p>McKinsey &amp; Company (2022). Strategic primer on DTs from a major consulting firm. Definition, business value, implementation examples. Used for context but explicitly not used as a definition source — the project rejects "the McKinsey definition" frame in the zine.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>business-value</code> · <code>adoption</code> · <code>consulting</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/operations/our-insights/digital-twins-what-could-they-do-for-your-business" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mckinsey.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="19">
          <span class="tag">professional</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>NTT Data — Reimagining Insurance Risk Assessment with Digital Twins</h4>
          <p>NTT Data (2024). Argues for a shift from static actuarial tables to real-time dynamic risk modelling via DTs. Direct application to underwriting — one of the audiences this project specifically excluded after the audience-narrowing iteration.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>risk</code> · <code>underwriting</code> · <code>real-time-modeling</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://insurance.nttdata.com/post/reimagining-insurance-risk-assessment-with-digital-twins" target="_blank" rel="noopener">insurance.nttdata.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="20">
          <span class="tag">professional</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>TechPolicy Press — Digital Twins Demand a New Social Contract</h4>
          <p>Tech Policy Press (2024). Argues that mass creation of digital twins of people requires a new social contract: new rules on consent, transparency, and data control. Introduces the Minimally Viable Permissibility Principle (<code>MVPP</code>).</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>ethics</code> · <code>social-contract</code> · <code>consent-design</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.techpolicy.press/digital-twins-demand-a-new-social-contract/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">techpolicy.press ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li data-n="21">
          <span class="tag">professional</span>
          <span class="badge badge--green">open access</span>
          <h4>The Actuary — The Power of Two: Digital Twins in Insurance</h4>
          <p>The Actuary, IFoA (2024). Profession-internal review for actuaries. How DTs can be used in risk modeling, pricing, and claims management. The view from inside the actuarial profession on what DT adoption changes.</p>
          <p class="meta">themes: <code>actuarial</code> · <code>pricing</code> · <code>claims</code></p>
          <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 6px;">
            <a href="https://www.theactuary.com/2024/04/04/power-two-digital-twins-insurance" target="_blank" rel="noopener">theactuary.com ↗</a>
          </p>
        </li>

      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== EXPORT / TERMINAL HINT ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="export-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Export · machine-readable</span>
      <h2 id="export-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Take the bibliography with you.</h2>
      <p class="lead" data-reveal data-delay="2">
        A consolidated <code>BibTeX</code> file and a plain-text APA 7
        export will be linked here once the manuscript is finalized at the
        end of D2 (zine submission).
      </p>

      <blockquote class="pullquote" data-reveal data-delay="3">
        <strong>digital-twins.bib</strong> · pending · attaches with D2.<br>
        <strong>digital-twins-apa7.txt</strong> · pending · attaches with D2.<br>
        Citation style: APA 7th edition. Continuous numbering 01–21.
      </blockquote>

      <p class="tag-row" style="margin-top: 24px;" data-reveal data-delay="4">
        <span class="badge badge--green">14 open access</span>
        <span class="badge badge--orange">3 UNF library</span>
        <span class="badge badge--blue">3 registration</span>
        <span class="badge badge--orange">1 paywalled summary</span>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== HOW TO ACCESS ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" id="access" aria-labelledby="access-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Practical note</span>
      <h2 id="access-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">How to access these sources</h2>
      <ul class="list-clean">
        <li><strong>Open access (14 of 21):</strong> click the link, the PDF or full text is free. This includes all GAO, EDPB, OPC Canada, the open-access peer-reviewed papers, and the professional/trade publications.</li>
        <li><strong>Paywalled academic (3 of 21):</strong> Hornik &amp; Rachamim (Springer), McColl-Kennedy et al. (Emerald), Quach et al. (SAGE). Access through a university library: at UNF, this is via <a href="https://library.unf.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">library.unf.edu ↗</a> → Databases → SpringerLink / Emerald Insight / SAGE Journals.</li>
        <li><strong>Registration-gated (3 of 21):</strong> Altair, Capgemini, KPMG. Free, but require an email-form sign-up before download.</li>
        <li><strong>Commercial (1 of 21):</strong> MRFR market report — only the executive summary is free; the full report is paid.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="muted" style="font-size: var(--fs-sm); margin-top: 16px; font-family: var(--ff-mono);">
        Last verified <span data-updated="2026-04-30">2026-04-30</span>. Some publisher URLs may shift over time; if a link breaks, the DOI or title-and-author search will still resolve.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== METHODOLOGY NOTE ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="method-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Selection criteria</span>
      <h2 id="method-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">How these sources were picked</h2>
      <p>
        Each source was selected against four criteria: relevance to the
        research question (digital twins in customer-facing auto insurance),
        recency (>80% from 2023 onward, with one foundational 2022 entry),
        traceability (every claim on this site points to one of these
        twenty-one), and source diversity across peer-reviewed academic
        work, industry reports, regulators, and practitioner publications.
        The full inclusion-and-exclusion protocol — including which sources
        were considered and dropped, and why — lives in the
        <a href="./methodology.html">methodology page</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== CTA ===== -->
